#compdef aspen
# =============================================================================
# aspen — Passerine's package manager (cargo-style scaffold + build runner).
#         Passerine is a small, extensible, dynamically-typed functional
#         programming language designed by Isaac "slightknack" Clayton
#         for **concise expression with little code**.  Distinguished by
#         FIRST-CLASS ALGEBRAIC EFFECTS (modeled after Eff / Koka),
#         HYGIENIC LISP-STYLE MACROS that operate on the syntax tree,
#         and a Pratt-parser-driven grammar that allows user-defined
#         infix operators with precedence.  Compiles to a custom
#         stack-based bytecode VM written in Rust.  Inspired by Wren
#         (Bob Nystrom's small embedded scripting language), Lua (table
#         semantics), Standard ML (algebraic data types + pattern
#         matching), and Racket (macro hygiene).  Used in research
#         contexts and as an exemplar for "what a modern small
#         dynamically-typed language can look like" — featured in
#         compiler-construction tutorials and Hacker News PL discussion.
#
# Author:  Isaac Clayton (slightknack — Cambridge UK PL hobbyist; designed
#          Passerine starting 2020 while in high school, continued through
#          undergrad CS; Passerine is paired with `passerine-aspen` the
#          package manager + `passerine-derive` the proc-macro derive
#          for Rust-side bindings)
# Source:  https://github.com/vrtbl/passerine
# CLI:     passerine-aspen/src/cli.rs (uses structopt; ALREADY documented
#          Rust CLI library variant — but Passerine is a NEW LANGUAGE)
# Library: structopt 0.3 (TeXitoi/structopt — predecessor of clap-derive)
# License: MIT
# Status:  Stable — 1091+ stars on vrtbl/passerine; aspen v0.5.1; the
#          canonical package manager + entry-point for working with
#          Passerine packages (.pn source files + aspen.toml manifest).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — 61ST DOCUMENTED LANGUAGE
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# its 61ST LANGUAGE (Passerine, via aspen).  Passerine joins the taxonomy
# as the first **algebraic-effects-with-hygienic-macros functional
# language** in the documented set — a niche occupied historically by
# Eff (Andrej Bauer), Koka (Daan Leijen / Microsoft Research), and the
# original Lisp / Scheme macro tradition.  Where prior small-functional
# entries (Yeti R??, Pure R??, min R??) bring different design points,
# Passerine is the FIRST documented language to combine ALGEBRAIC
# EFFECTS + HYGIENIC MACROS + USER-DEFINED INFIX OPERATORS in a single
# small dynamic VM.  New language tally: 61.  Top-language tally
# remains Rust=35 / Go=35 / TS-Node=35 (THREE-WAY TIE).  Taxonomy now
# spans 252 cross-language CLI library variants across 61 documented
# languages.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS PASSERINE AND WHY IS aspen THE 61ST LANGUAGE'S BINARY?
#
# Passerine (https://github.com/vrtbl/passerine) is **Isaac Clayton's
# "small, extensible programming language designed for concise expression
# with little code"** — a dynamically-typed functional language with
# stack-based bytecode VM, designed primarily as a thought experiment
# in "what could a modern small scripting language look like if it
# inherited from Wren, Lua, SML, and Racket simultaneously".
#
# Passerine's design points distinguishing it from other documented
# languages:
#
#   1. ALGEBRAIC EFFECTS AS FIRST-CLASS LANGUAGE FEATURE — Passerine
#      models side effects (I/O, exceptions, state, async) through
#      ALGEBRAIC EFFECT HANDLERS rather than monads (Haskell) or
#      ad-hoc exception machinery (Python, Lua, JS).  An effect is
#      declared with `effect`, raised with `perform`, handled by a
#      `handle` block.  This is the OCaml-5 / Koka / Eff school of
#      effects, brought into a small VM:
#         effect Random with
#             gen () -> Int,
#         end
#
#         let main () =
#             handle
#                 (rand_a, rand_b) = (perform gen (), perform gen ())
#                 print (rand_a + rand_b)
#             with
#                 gen () k -> resume k (random 0 100)
#             end
#         end
#      Effects are CHECKED STATICALLY at compile time (which effect
#      handlers must be in scope for a function body's perform calls).
#      Compare:
#        Haskell:    monads + monad transformers — no algebraic effects
#                     by default (effectful packages exist as libraries)
#        OCaml 5:    similar `effect ... with ... end` syntax (Passerine
#                     borrows the surface syntax)
#        Koka:       effect rows with subtype polymorphism — more
#                     research-leaning
#        Passerine:  effects-as-Lisp-friendly-handlers, opinionated
#                     small-VM implementation.
#
#   2. HYGIENIC LISP-STYLE MACROS THAT OPERATE ON SYNTAX TREE —
#      Passerine ships a Racket-flavored MACRO SYSTEM where macros are
#      named `syntax` and operate on the parse tree (after the Pratt
#      parser but before AST checking):
#         syntax 'unless cond then body do' = `if not $cond then $body do`
#      The macro receives the matched syntax tree and produces a new
#      syntax tree.  Hygiene is automatic — local names introduced by
#      a macro don't collide with caller's names.  Compare:
#        Lisp / Scheme:  long tradition of macros — Passerine borrows
#                         this lineage explicitly
#        Rust:           proc-macros (more powerful but separate language)
#        Nemerle R505:   macro system at compiler level (inspired F#
#                         computation expressions per R505 commit)
#        Passerine:      Racket-inspired hygienic macros with template-
#                         like quasi-quotation `` ` ``+`$name`.
#
#   3. USER-DEFINED INFIX OPERATORS WITH PRECEDENCE — Passerine's
#      grammar is Pratt-parsed, and users can ADD NEW INFIX OPERATORS
#      with custom precedence at the source level:
#         syntax '$a `pow` $b' precedence 8 = ...
#      The `precedence N` clause inserts the new operator into the
#      Pratt parser's precedence table at level N.  Compare:
#        Haskell:    `infixl 6 +`, `infixr 5 :` — declarative infix
#                     declarations, fixed at parser level
#        OCaml:      no user-defined infix beyond the lex-class rules
#        Scala:      symbolic method names work as infix automatically
#        F# / Nemerle: no user-defined infix
#        Passerine:  EXPLICIT `precedence N` clause as part of macro/
#                     syntax declaration — operator's precedence is
#                     defined at SOURCE LEVEL, not via compiler flag.
#
#   4. TABLE-AS-EVERY-DATA-STRUCTURE (LUA HERITAGE) — Passerine inherits
#      from Lua the design choice that **TABLES ARE THE ONLY
#      AGGREGATE DATA STRUCTURE**.  Records, arrays, structs,
#      key-value maps, sets, namespaces — all are tables (where a
#      table is a heterogeneous keyed map).  Compare:
#        Lua:        canonical example — every aggregate is a table
#        JavaScript: objects + arrays are conceptually similar but
#                     formally separate types
#        Python:     dicts + lists + sets + tuples + namedtuples
#                     — distinct types
#        Passerine:  TABLES ONLY — like Lua, but with hygienic macros
#                     + algebraic effects layered on top.
#
#   5. STACK-BASED BYTECODE VM WRITTEN IN RUST — Passerine's runtime is
#      a custom **stack-based bytecode VM written in Rust**.  Compiles
#      `.pn` source via the `passerine` crate to bytecode, then
#      executes via the stack VM.  Compare:
#        Lua:        register-based VM (in C)
#        Python:     stack-based VM (in C)
#        Wren:       stack-based VM (in C)
#        Lobster:    custom VM (in C++)
#        Passerine:  STACK-BASED VM in RUST — distinguishes Passerine
#                     among small embeddable languages by being
#                     memory-safe at the implementation level (no
#                     C-side undefined behavior).
#
# THE aspen PACKAGE-MANAGER CLI (CARGO-STYLE)
#
# aspen is to Passerine what cargo is to Rust — the canonical interface
# for working with packages.  An aspen package is a directory containing
# `aspen.toml` (manifest) and `src/main.pn` (entrypoint).  The CLI
# surface in `passerine-aspen/src/cli.rs` is defined via structopt:
#
#   #[derive(StructOpt, Debug)]
#   pub struct Package {
#       #[structopt(default_value = ".", parse(from_os_str = package_dir))]
#       pub path: PathBuf,
#   }
#
#   #[derive(StructOpt, Debug)]
#   #[structopt(name = "Aspen", bin_name = "aspen", about)]
#   pub enum Aspen {
#       /// Creates a new Passerine package
#       New(Package),
#       /// Runs the specified package
#       Run(Package),
#       /// Drop into the Passerine REPL
#       Repl,
#       // Update,
#       // Publish,
#       // Test,
#       // Bench,
#       // Doc,
#       // Debug,
#   }
#
# Implemented subcommands (in v0.5.1):
#   aspen new [PATH]      Create a new Passerine package skeleton at PATH
#                          (defaults to '.', creates aspen.toml + src/main.pn)
#   aspen run [PATH]      Run the package at PATH (defaults to '.';
#                          loads aspen.toml, compiles src/main.pn,
#                          executes via Passerine VM)
#   aspen repl            Drop into the Passerine REPL (interactive
#                          evaluation; type expressions, see results +
#                          inferred shapes)
#
# Stubbed-out future subcommands (declared but unimplemented):
#   update, publish, test, bench, doc, debug
#
# Manifest (aspen.toml) example:
#   [package]
#   name = "my-package"
#   version = "0.1.0"
#   authors = ["You <you@example.com>"]
#
#   [dependencies]
#   stdlib = "0.1"
#
# Entry point (src/main.pn) example:
#   syntax 'unless $cond then $body' = `if not $cond then $body`
#
#   effect Console with
#       println: String -> (),
#   end
#
#   let main () =
#       handle
#           perform println "Hello, Passerine!"
#       with
#           println msg k -> print msg; resume k ()
#       end
#       unless 1 = 2 then
#           print "math works"
#       end
#   end
#
# PASSERINE LANGUAGE TIES TO OTHER LANGUAGES IN THE TAXONOMY:
#
#   * Lua — Passerine inherits the table-as-everything design
#   * Wren (wren_cli IN CORPUS) — Passerine cites Wren explicitly
#       in its design rationale; both are small embedded scripting VMs
#   * SML / OCaml — algebraic data types + pattern matching syntax
#   * Racket / Scheme — hygienic macro tradition
#   * OCaml 5 / Eff / Koka — algebraic-effects-with-handlers design
#   * Nemerle R505 (IN CORPUS) — macro-rich functional language with
#       similar "language extensibility via macros" philosophy
#   * Crystal's Admiral, Pony's cli stdlib, Beef's parsing —
#       comparison-set of "small-language with self-hosting tooling"
#
# REAL-WORLD aspen USAGE (from upstream + community):
#
#   * Passerine PL tutorials use aspen to demonstrate the language
#       (run "aspen new hello" + edit src/main.pn + "aspen run")
#   * Passerine's own stdlib (vrtbl/passerine-stdlib) is structured
#       as an aspen package
#   * Community examples on the Passerine Discord and PL community
#       blogs (slightknack's own personal blog has multiple Passerine
#       tutorials using the aspen CLI)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# ASPEN'S CLI SURFACE (verbatim from passerine-aspen/src/cli.rs)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   aspen <SUBCOMMAND> [args...]
#
# Subcommands (implemented in v0.5.1):
#   new    [PATH]                  Create a new Passerine package skeleton
#                                   (default PATH: ".")
#   run    [PATH]                  Run the specified package (default ".")
#   repl                           Drop into the Passerine REPL
#
# Subcommands (declared but unimplemented in 0.5.1):
#   update                         Update dependency versions
#   publish                        Publish to the Passerine package registry
#   test                           Run the package's test suite
#   bench                          Run benchmarks
#   doc                            Generate API documentation
#   debug                          Drop into the Passerine debugger
#
# Built-in structopt flags (always reserved):
#   -h, --help                     Show help (structopt built-in)
#   -V, --version                  Show version (structopt built-in)
#
# Typical usage:
#   $ aspen new my-package          # creates ./my-package/aspen.toml + src/
#   $ cd my-package
#   $ aspen run                     # compiles + runs src/main.pn
#   $ aspen run /path/to/other      # runs a package at an explicit path
#   $ aspen repl                    # interactive REPL
#
# Package layout (created by `aspen new`):
#   my-package/
#       aspen.toml                 # package manifest (name, version,
#                                   #  authors, dependencies)
#       src/
#           main.pn                # entry-point Passerine source file
#       .gitignore                 # ignores target/
#
# Companion tools:
#   passerine (library)            # the Rust crate that aspen wraps;
#                                   # used by other tools that want to
#                                   # embed the Passerine VM
#   passerine-derive               # proc-macro derive crate for
#                                   # exposing Rust types to Passerine
#
# =============================================================================

_aspen() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    local -a subcommands

    subcommands=(
        'new:create a new Passerine package skeleton'
        'run:run the specified package'
        'repl:drop into the Passerine REPL'
        'update:update dependency versions (unimplemented in 0.5.1)'
        'publish:publish to package registry (unimplemented in 0.5.1)'
        'test:run test suite (unimplemented in 0.5.1)'
        'bench:run benchmarks (unimplemented in 0.5.1)'
        'doc:generate API documentation (unimplemented in 0.5.1)'
        'debug:drop into the Passerine debugger (unimplemented in 0.5.1)'
        'help:show help'
    )

    _arguments -C \
        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
        '(-V --version)'{-V,--version}'[show version]' \
        '1: :->cmd' \
        '*::arg:->args' && ret=0

    case $state in
        (cmd)
            _describe -t commands 'aspen command' subcommands && ret=0
            ;;
        (args)
            case $line[1] in
                (new|run)
                    _arguments \
                        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                        '*:package path:_directories' \
                        && ret=0
                    ;;
                (repl|update|publish|test|bench|doc|debug)
                    _arguments \
                        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                        && ret=0
                    ;;
            esac
            ;;
    esac

    return ret
}

_aspen "$@"
